A worker came to repair the kitchen floor. I pretended I was just working from home, actually editing Can't Stop Wanting To.
If only this damned file would open. (OneDrive is really shit.)
*The hacker's voice* I've entered.
He started drilling, making an incredibly loud noise. Great.
Turned on the air purifier to max; it felt a bit overpowering, but I did smell sawdust, so it wasn't entirely unwarranted. Besides, he was against wearing masks. And I do need to protect myself, don't I?
I really want to go back to sleep, but I can only do that after he leaves.
Good news is, Chapter Four is finally done!
Chapter Five is very long and super anxiety-inducing. Yay! It's so exciting.
Searching and replacing...➡️ ellipsis, there are 54 in this chapter 😅
But I still need to stick to this point. Most natural language is disjointed, especially when people are emotionally charged.
The floor repairman is using a vacuum cleaner to clean up, hoping that means he's nearly done.
He went out (seemed like he was cutting something). I sneaked a peek at the progress. There's still a lot left to do :(.
Chapter five has seven more pages. This is still my favorite chapter, and the draft is in good shape, mainly involving formatting adjustments and some minor tweaks to active voice and conciseness. But I really need a break, a cup of tea, and that guy is still busy in my kitchen.
He started the vacuum again. Hopefully, that's a good sign.
The worker who fixed the kitchen floor has left!
He told me that he had quoted the price for the entire floor repair, but the landlord was too tightfisted and only agreed to pay for the maintenance of the rotten area near the door. That feels much better.
I was drinking tea in the garden while the air purifier in the kitchen was working hard to clean the air in the room!
